{
  "doc_id": "54278",
  "text": "Cancer cells express a typically aberrant protein repertoire compared to that of normal cells. These aberrations, whether functional (drivers) or non-functional (passengers), have the potential to generate peptide antigens that are not (or are only partially) subjected to central or peripheral tolerance. As such, when presented by human leukocyte antigen (HLA) complexes on the surface of cancer cells, these antigens might lead to recognition by cytotoxic T-cells and, eventually, to immuno-mediated tumor clearance [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Tumors, however, can develop sophisticated escape mechanisms [CITATION_3] and immune evasion is now recognised as one of the hallmarks of cancer [CITATION_4] .",
